Palp: Cymbium with projection (
Fig. 6A
); prolateral side of paracymbium unpigmented and unsclerotized, with numerous setae and spines at tip (
Fig. 6A
); contrategulum with denticulate margin (
Fig. 6A, D, G
); tegulum with serrate marginal apophysis and dorsal extension of terminal apophysis, as well as smooth thumb-shaped terminal apophysis reaching underneath it in retrolateral view (
Fig. 6C, F
); conductor situated ventro-proximally on embolus, with proximal portion relatively narrow, and distally with two slender apical spines (
Fig. 6B, E
); embolus sclerotized with wide and flat opening (
Fig. 6A, D
).

Female genitalia: Median pair of receptacular clusters situated at anterior margin of bursa copulatrix with ribbed genital stalks relatively close basally but separated from each other distally; lateral pair smaller than median pair, spherical, situated more dorsally with obscure genital stalks; posterior part of genital area irregular arc (
Fig. 6K, O
).

Variation. Males and females vary in body size. The range of measurements in males ( N = 12): BL 9.20–15.19, CL 4.51–6.33, CW 3.40–5.73, OL 4.42–8.19, OW 3.04–6.63; females ( N = 16): BL 10.86–15.56, CL 4.79–6.97, CW 4.12–6.34, OL 4.87–8.07, OW 3.69–6.18. Female genitalia also exhibits considerable intraspecific variation: the genital stalks of median pair are slightly curved and with smooth surface as well as wide distance, the posterior part of the genital area rectangular with a notch in the middle ( Fig. 6H, L ); or the genital stalks of median pair slightly vertical; the lateral pair cylindrical; the posterior part of genital area rectangular (
Fig. 6I , M
); or the genital stalks of median pair with several small granula and tilted outward ( Fig. 6J, N )
